 monitoring the fetal heart rate than external sensors, as it is directly attached to the fetus, reducing the risk of motion interference or signal loss. In the perinatal stage, healthcare professionals rely on the FSE and its cable to provide immediate and precise data, enabling timely interventions to improve neonatal outcomes and maternal safety. This application is critical in detecting potential complications such as fetal hypoxia or abnormal heart rhythms, which could otherwise go unnoticed with external monitoring.<p>Additionally, the perinatal segment benefits from the continuous development of advanced monitoring technologies that offer real-time insights into the fetal heart rate. These technologies allow for more accurate assessments and help healthcare providers to make informed decisions regarding the timing of delivery or the need for interventions such as cesarean sections or instrumental deliveries. The growing demand for non-invasive, effective, and continuous fetal monitoring solutions is anticipated to drive market growth within the perinatal segment. Furthermore, the rising incidence of high-risk pregnancies, including those involving maternal conditions like hypertension or diabetes, has led to an increased focus on perinatal care. This heightened awareness among healthcare providers and expectant mothers about the importance of fetal health monitoring further strengthens the market for FSEs and cables.<h2>Labor and Delivery</h2><p>The labor and delivery segment is another significant application area for the fetal spiral electrode and cable market. During labor, it is crucial to monitor the fetal heart rate to assess the fetus’s response to uterine contractions and to ensure there are no signs of distress. The FSE, attached directly to the fetal scalp, provides continuous and more accurate readings of the fetal heart rate compared to external devices, especially during active labor. This method helps detect any abnormal heart patterns, such as 